'''Kiritsuma-zukuri''' (切妻造) is a traditional {{ill|roof style|ja|屋根|12=draft}} characterized by two sloping planes meeting at the ridge (棟), forming a triangular gable shape resembling an open book. In a broader sense, it refers to buildings employing this roof design and is also called a '''gable roof'''.

== Basic Terminology ==

=== Hirairi and Tsumairi ===
In Japanese architectural terminology, the long side or the side parallel to the ridge (大棟) of a building is referred to as the "Hira" (平), while the short side or the side perpendicular to the ridge is called "Tsuma" (妻). 

The terms "'''Hirairi'''" (平入り) and "'''Tsumairi'''" (妻入り) denote whether the main entrance is located on the Hira or Tsuma side. These classifications are often used in {{ill|Japanese townhouses|ja|町屋|12=draft}} or {{ill|shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|12=draft}}. Hirairi indicates an entrance on the Hira side, creating an a11roachable streetscape, while Tsumairi places the entrance on the Tsuma side<ref>{{Cite book|author=今和次郎|year=1943|title=改稿　日本の民家|publisher=相模書房|pages=P.39}}</ref>.

<gallery widths="150px" heights="150px">
File:Nara Old Building Yoshioka.jpg|Hirairi {{ill|townhouses|ja|町家|12=draft}}<br>Nara Prefecture, {{ill|Naramachi|ja|ならまち|12=draft}}
File:Kyoto gion02.jpg|Hirairi townhouses in {{ill|Gion|ja|祇園|12=draft}}<br>Kyoto Prefecture
File:Kawasaki(Ise)-01.JPG|Tsumairi farmhouse<br>Mie Prefecture, {{ill|Kawasaki, Ise|ja|河崎 (伊勢市)|12=draft}}
File:Izumozaki cityscape.jpg|Tsumairi streetscape<br>Niigata Prefecture, {{ill|Izumozaki|ja|出雲崎町|12=draft}}
</gallery>

=== Keta and Hari ===
The {{ill|Keta|ja|桁|12=draft}} refers to the horizontal beam running parallel to the ridge, su11orting the roof's load. Its length and orientation are termed "Keta-yuki" (桁行) or "Keta direction." Conversely, the {{ill|Hari|ja|梁|12=draft}} runs perpendicular to the ridge, and its length and direction are called "Hari-ma" (梁間) or "Hari direction."

== Gable Roof in Shrine Architecture ==
In {{ill|Japanese shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|12=draft}}, the gable roof (Kiritsuma-zukuri) is often used in main sanctuaries (本殿), as well as its derivative, {{ill|Nagare-zukuri|ja|流造|12=draft}}.

=== Ridge (棟) ===
The ridge (棟) of the roof in shrine architecture is adorned with {{ill|Katsuogi|ja|鰹木|12=draft}}, horizontal wooden beams that serve as decorative elements and weights.

=== Gable (妻) ===
The triangular portion of the roof's gable, known as the {{ill|Hafu|ja|破風|12=draft}}, is often extended outward to form decorative {{ill|Chigi|ja|千木|12=draft}}. Chigi tips are traditionally said to indicate whether the shrine enshrines a male or female deity, with horizontal cuts symbolizing female deities and vertical cuts male deities.

<gallery widths="150px" heights="150px">
File:Sagawa art museum01s3200.jpg|Modern {{ill|Kiritsuma-zukuri|ja|切妻造|12=draft}}<br>{{ill|Sagawa Art Museum|ja|佐川美術館|12=draft}}, Shiga Prefecture
File:Linyuan Gate Jiyuan.jpg|Kiritsuma-zukuri Daoist temple<br>{{ill|Jiyuan|ja|済源市|12=draft}}, Henan Province, China
File:Sudeoksa 02.JPG|Kiritsuma-zukuri Buddhist temple<br>{{ill|Sudeoksa|ja|修徳寺|12=draft}}, South Korea
</gallery>

